  "opinion": "As a nurse with a bachelor's degree who grew up in Rome, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can affect people's confidence. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's real. It happens when someone feels their group's stereotype is being tested, like when a girl in math class worries she'll be seen as 'not good at numbers.' Back when I was in school, my father worked in construction and my mother was a teacher, so I never really thought about being 'less capable' in science. But now, I see it in my patients and in the students I volunteer with. In my nursing practice, I've noticed that women sometimes hesitate to ask questions in STEM-heavy fields because they fear being judged. We should address it by creating safe spaces where people feel valued for their individual abilities, not just their group. For example, in my community, we have workshops where people can learn without fear of judgment. It's important to be gentle and patient—many people don't realize how much their confidence impacts their performance. I believe that with empathy and support, we can help everyone reach their full potential, whether they're in a hospital or a classroom.",
